\subsection{Tmux-Managed Commands}

Tmux-launched commands need a different waiting strategy from direct
[[subprocess.run]].  The [[tmux split-window]] and [[new-window]]
commands return as soon as the pane exists, not when the program inside
the pane finishes.  To preserve [[track start]]'s launch semantics we therefore
make tmux notify us when the pane's command exits.

The main race is at startup: a very short-lived command could finish
before we manage to install any hook on its pane.  We avoid that by
launching a tiny shell wrapper that first blocks on a tmux
[[wait-for]] channel.  Once the parent has learned the new [[pane_id]]
and installed pane-scoped exit hooks, it signals that channel so the
wrapped command can start.

The wrapper intentionally uses a plain non-login [[/bin/sh]] process.
This wrapper is not a user shell session---it is just a rendezvous point
between tmux and the real command---so reading login startup files would
only add risk.  A login shell can emit errors, alter the environment, or
delay startup before the hook handshake is in place.

Normal completion now flows through the wrapper itself: after the child
command exits, the wrapper records its exit status and signals the
waiting parent directly.  That keeps the common [[exit]]/Ctrl+D path
independent of tmux hook delivery.  We still install pane-scoped exit
hooks as a fallback for abnormal cases such as an explicit
[[kill-pane]]---the wrapper cannot run cleanup after it has been killed,
but tmux can still report that the pane died.

Both paths share one atomic completion guard.  The first path to claim
that guard writes the status file, runs any follow-up shell command, and
wakes the parent.  Later signals become harmless no-ops instead of
double-running cleanup.

