\subsubsection{Suspend and Resume Helpers}

The suspend helper stops only the labels that are currently active
in the worker's session---any label already stopped (by the user
or another process) is silently skipped.  It writes the actually
stopped labels to the state file, so the state file records the
truth rather than the caller's optimistic assumption.

<<helper functions>>=
def suspend_tracking_labels(
    who: str,
    labels: List[str],
    pane_id: str,
) -> None:
    """Suspend tracking for a pane that lost focus.

    Stops whichever of ``labels`` are still active and
    writes them to the pane's suspend state file.
    """
    session = load_active_session(who)
    active = set(session.get_active_labels())
    to_suspend = [
        lbl for lbl in labels if lbl in active
    ]
    if not to_suspend:
        return

    stop_tracking_labels(
        who=who,
        labels=to_suspend,
        quiet_if_missing=True,
        update_tmux_context=False,
    )
    state_path = suspend_state_path(pane_id, who)
    write_suspend_state(state_path, to_suspend)
@

We delete the state file \emph{before} restarting labels so that a
crash between the two steps never causes a double-resume---losing
an unfocused session is preferable to silently double-booking time.
If the file is absent (pane exited while unfocused, or user manually
stopped everything), the resume is a no-op.

<<helper functions>>=
def resume_tracking_labels(
    who: str,
    pane_id: str,
) -> None:
    """Resume tracking for a pane that regained focus.

    Reads the suspend state file and restarts the
    labels recorded there.  Deletes the file afterwards.
    """
    state_path = suspend_state_path(pane_id, who)
    labels = read_suspend_state(state_path)
    if not labels:
        return

    delete_suspend_state(state_path)
    start_tracking_labels(
        who=who,
        labels=labels,
        start_time=datetime.datetime.now(),
        update_tmux_context=False,
    )
@

To implement \enquote{selected in any attached client} semantics we ask
tmux for the tracked window's [[window_active_clients]] count.  A
positive count means at least one client currently has the window
selected, regardless of whether that client is the original terminal.

<<helper functions>>=
def tmux_window_has_active_client(
    window_id: str,
) -> bool:
    """Return whether any attached client currently selects ``window_id``."""
    try:
        result = subprocess.run(
            [
                "tmux",
                "display-message",
                "-p",
                "-t",
                window_id,
                "#{window_active_clients}",
            ],
            capture_output=True,
            text=True,
            check=True,
        )
    except (subprocess.CalledProcessError, OSError):
        return False
    try:
        return int(result.stdout.strip() or "0") > 0
    except ValueError:
        return False
@

For nested [[track]] commands inside a tracked tmux window, we must not
trust inherited environment variables such as [[TMUX_WINDOW_ID]].  A new
tmux window created with [[^b c]] would inherit the shell environment
from the old one, falsely claiming to belong to the tracked window.
Instead we derive the current [[window_id]] from the live [[TMUX_PANE]]
every time.

<<helper functions>>=
def get_tmux_window_id_for_pane(
    pane_id: str,
) -> Optional[str]:
    """Return the tmux window id containing ``pane_id``."""
    try:
        result = subprocess.run(
            [
                "tmux",
                "display-message",
                "-p",
                "-t",
                pane_id,
                "#{window_id}",
            ],
            capture_output=True,
            text=True,
            check=True,
        )
    except (subprocess.CalledProcessError, OSError):
        return None
    window_id = result.stdout.strip()
    if not window_id:
        return None
    return window_id
@

Before querying tmux for the current window, we check whether any
tracked-window state files exist at all.  This avoids a subprocess call
to tmux in the common case where window tracking is not in use.

<<helper functions>>=
def has_tracked_window_state(
    who: str,
) -> bool:
    """Return whether this worker currently has tracked windows."""
    pattern = f"window_labels_*_{sanitize_who(who)}.json"
    return any(get_tracking_dir().glob(pattern))
@

Enumerating tracked windows and workers is needed by the session-scoped
dispatcher command, which must scan all tracked windows across all
workers to decide which to suspend or resume.

<<helper functions>>=
def list_tracked_window_ids(
    who: str,
) -> List[str]:
    """Return tracked tmux window ids for ``who`` from state files."""
    pattern = f"window_labels_*_{sanitize_who(who)}.json"
    prefix = "window_labels_window_"
    suffix = f"_{sanitize_who(who)}.json"
    window_ids = []
    for path in sorted(get_tracking_dir().glob(pattern)):
        name = path.name
        if not name.startswith(prefix) or not name.endswith(suffix):
            continue
        encoded = name[len(prefix):-len(suffix)]
        window_ids.append("@" + encoded)
    return window_ids
@

Worker discovery scans the tracking directory rather than maintaining a
separate registry, keeping the state self-describing and avoiding stale
entries.

<<helper functions>>=
def list_workers_with_tracked_windows() -> List[str]:
    """Return workers that currently have tracked tmux windows."""
    prefix = "window_labels_window_"
    suffix = ".json"
    workers = set()
    for path in get_tracking_dir().glob("window_labels_*.json"):
        name = path.name
        if not name.startswith(prefix) or not name.endswith(suffix):
            continue
        stem = name[len(prefix):-len(suffix)]
        if "_" not in stem:
            continue
        _, worker = stem.split("_", 1)
        workers.add(worker)
    return sorted(workers)
@

The dispatcher must restrict its actions to windows that belong to the
triggering tmux session, since multiple sessions may coexist on the same
server.  We query tmux for the window's current session rather than
caching it, because windows can be moved between sessions.

<<helper functions>>=
def window_belongs_to_session(
    window_id: str,
    session_id: str,
) -> bool:
    """Return whether ``window_id`` currently belongs to ``session_id``."""
    try:
        result = subprocess.run(
            [
                "tmux",
                "display-message",
                "-p",
                "-t",
                window_id,
                "#{session_id}",
            ],
            capture_output=True,
            text=True,
            check=True,
        )
    except (subprocess.CalledProcessError, OSError):
        return False
    return result.stdout.strip() == session_id
@

The main entry point for nested commands combines the guards above: it
resolves the live window from [[TMUX_PANE]], checks for existing
tracked-window state, and only returns a [[window_id]] when the window
is already tracked by nytid.

<<helper functions>>=
def get_current_tracked_window_id(
    who: str,
) -> Optional[str]:
    """Return the live tmux window id if it is already tracked."""
    pane_id = os.environ.get("TMUX_PANE")
    if not pane_id:
        return None
    if not has_tracked_window_state(who):
        return None
    window_id = get_tmux_window_id_for_pane(pane_id)
    if not window_id:
        return None
    if read_window_labels(window_id, who) is None:
        return None
    return window_id
@

\subsubsection{Hidden Detached Commands}

The focus hooks run inside tmux's [[run-shell]], which launches a
fresh Python process.  We provide three hidden CLI commands for this
purpose: a pane-scoped suspend/resume pair, plus a window-sync command
that reevaluates all tracked windows in a session.  They follow the
same pattern as [[_stop-detached]].

Window sync uses a declarative approach: it reads every tracked
window's labels file, computes which labels \emph{should} be active
(the union of labels from currently selected windows) and which are
\emph{managed} (the union of labels from all tracked windows in the
session), then converges the running state by stopping managed labels
that should not be active and starting labels that should be active
but are not yet running.  Because the window labels file is the sole
source of truth---no intermediate suspend-state files are
involved---there is no stale state that can cause labels to leak
between windows.

The source of truth is deliberately scoped per window, however, not per
label across the whole session.  If the user manually stops [[devel]]
while inside tracked window~A, [[track stop]] removes [[devel]] from
window~A's file.  Sync will therefore not resurrect [[devel]] when
window~A becomes selected again.  If tracked window~B still declares
[[devel]], that declaration remains valid for window~B.

<<argument and option definitions>>=
pane_id_opt = typer.Option(
    "--pane-id",
    help="Tmux pane ID (internal use)",
)
window_id_opt = typer.Option(
    "--window-id",
    help="Tmux window ID (internal use)",
)
session_id_opt = typer.Option(
    "--session-id",
    help="Tmux session ID (internal use)",
)
@

<<detached suspend command>>=
@cli.command(
    name="_suspend-detached", hidden=True
)
def suspend_detached(
    pane_id: Annotated[str, pane_id_opt],
    who: Annotated[str, who_opt] = default_username,
):
    """Suspend labels when a tracked pane loses focus."""
    labels = read_pane_labels(pane_id, who)
    if not labels:
        return
    suspend_tracking_labels(
        who=who, labels=labels, pane_id=pane_id,
    )
@

<<detached window sync command>>=
@cli.command(
    name="_sync-window-tracking-detached", hidden=True
)
def sync_window_tracking_detached(
    session_id: Annotated[str, session_id_opt],
):
    """Synchronize tracked window state for a tmux session.

    Converges running labels toward the declared window
    labels: stops managed labels that should not be active,
    starts labels that should be active but are not running.
    """
    for who in list_workers_with_tracked_windows():
        <<snapshot tracked windows for session>>
        if not managed_labels:
            continue
        <<converge running labels toward declared state>>
@

The snapshot phase iterates every tracked window in the session and
partitions labels into two sets.  [[managed_labels]] is the union of
labels from \emph{all} tracked windows---these are the labels the sync
is responsible for.  [[should_be_active]] is the subset contributed by
windows that currently have an attached client selecting them.  Labels
outside [[managed_labels]] (started manually or by pane tracking) are
left untouched.

<<snapshot tracked windows for session>>=
should_be_active = set()
managed_labels = set()
for window_id in list_tracked_window_ids(who):
    if not window_belongs_to_session(
        window_id, session_id,
    ):
        continue
    labels = read_window_labels(window_id, who)
    if not labels:
        continue
    managed_labels.update(labels)
    if tmux_window_has_active_client(window_id):
        should_be_active.update(labels)
@

Convergence compares the declared state against the running state and
issues the minimal set of stop and start operations.  A label shared
by two windows where only one is selected stays in
[[should_be_active]] and is never stopped---no explicit protection
set is needed because the set algebra handles it naturally.

<<converge running labels toward declared state>>=
session = load_active_session(who)
currently_running = set(session.get_active_labels())

to_stop = [
    lbl for lbl in managed_labels
    if lbl in currently_running
    and lbl not in should_be_active
]
if to_stop:
    stop_tracking_labels(
        who=who,
        labels=to_stop,
        quiet_if_missing=True,
        update_tmux_context=False,
    )

to_start = [
    lbl for lbl in should_be_active
    if lbl not in currently_running
]
if to_start:
    start_tracking_labels(
        who=who,
        labels=to_start,
        start_time=datetime.datetime.now(),
        update_tmux_context=False,
    )
@

