\subsubsection{Installing Focus Hooks}

Unlike the exit hooks, which use a pane-existence check (see
[[install_tmux_exit_hooks]]), focus hooks use tmux's format-string
pane-ID comparison ([[#{==:#{pane_id},...}]]).  The distinction
matters: exit hooks fire \emph{after} a pane dies, so we must ask
whether the tracked pane still exists; focus hooks fire while the
tracked pane is alive, so [[#{pane_id}]] correctly resolves to the
pane that gained or lost focus and we can compare it directly.

<<helper functions>>=
def install_tmux_focus_hooks(
    pane_id: str,
    who: str,
) -> None:
    """Install pane-focus-out and pane-focus-in hooks.

    The hooks use a format-string pane-ID guard (not the
    pane-existence check used by exit hooks) because
    focus events fire while the tracked pane is alive.
    """
    suspend_cmd = build_detached_suspend_command(
        who, pane_id,
    )
    resume_cmd = build_detached_resume_command(
        who, pane_id,
    )
    for hook_name, shell_cmd in (
        ("pane-focus-out", suspend_cmd),
        ("pane-focus-in", resume_cmd),
    ):
        guarded = (
            "if-shell -F "
            f"'#{{==:#{{pane_id}},{pane_id}}}' "
            f"{{ run-shell {shlex.quote(shell_cmd)} }}"
        )
        subprocess.run(
            [
                "tmux", "set-hook", "-p",
                "-t", pane_id,
                hook_name, guarded,
            ],
            check=True,
        )
@

Window launches cannot use [[pane-focus-out]] because terminal blur to a
browser would incorrectly suspend tracking.  Instead we install one
stable session-scoped dispatcher hook that coexists with any existing
tmux hooks for the same event.  On each relevant tmux event, that
dispatcher scans nytid's tracked-window state, then consults tmux's live
[[window_active_clients]] count to decide which windows should be
suspended or resumed.

Because multiple nytid launches may target the same tmux session, we
must avoid appending duplicate hook entries.  The
[[install_tmux_hook_once]] helper queries existing hooks first and skips
the append when the exact command string is already registered.

<<helper functions>>=
def install_tmux_hook_once(
    target: str,
    hook_name: str,
    command: str,
) -> None:
    """Append a tmux hook command once without clobbering others."""
    show_result = subprocess.run(
        ["tmux", "show-hooks", "-t", target],
        capture_output=True,
        text=True,
        check=False,
    )
    existing = show_result.stdout
    if command in existing:
        return
    subprocess.run(
        [
            "tmux", "set-hook", "-a",
            "-t", target,
            hook_name,
            command,
        ],
        check=True,
    )
@

With the idempotent installer in hand, we register session-scoped hooks
for all events that can change which window is selected.

<<helper functions>>=
def install_tmux_window_sync_hooks(
    session_id: str,
) -> None:
    """Install stable session hooks that dispatch window sync."""
    sync_cmd = build_detached_window_sync_command(session_id)
    hook_command = f"run-shell {shlex.quote(sync_cmd)}"
    hook_specs = (
        "session-window-changed",
        "client-session-changed",
        "client-attached",
        "client-detached",
    )
    for hook_name in hook_specs:
        install_tmux_hook_once(
            session_id,
            hook_name,
            hook_command,
        )
@

\subsubsection{Cleaning Up Suspend State on Pane Exit}

When a pane exits while unfocused, the focus-out hook has already
written a suspend state file that no focus-in will ever read.  Rather
than complicating [[_stop-detached]] with an optional [[--pane-id]]
argument (which would require the pane ID to be known before the
on-exit shell command is built), we install a lightweight cleanup
hook that removes both the suspend state file and the pane labels
file.

The hook runs as a second [[pane-exited]] handler.  Tmux 3.2+
allows multiple hooks on the same event by appending with
[[set-hook -a]].  The guard uses the same pane-existence check
as the main exit hooks (see above).

<<helper functions>>=
def install_tmux_suspend_cleanup_hook(
    pane_id: str,
    who: str,
) -> None:
    """Install a pane-exit hook that deletes suspend and pane-labels files."""
    state_file = suspend_state_path(pane_id, who)
    labels_file = pane_labels_path(pane_id, who)
    cleanup_cmd = (
        f"rm -f {shlex.quote(str(state_file))}"
        f" {shlex.quote(str(labels_file))}"
    )
    guarded = (
        "if-shell "
        f"'! tmux display-message -p -t {pane_id}"
        f' "" 2>/dev/null\' '
        f"{{ run-shell {shlex.quote(cleanup_cmd)} }}"
    )
    for hook_name in ("pane-exited", "pane-died"):
        subprocess.run(
            [
                "tmux", "set-hook", "-ap",
                "-t", pane_id,
                hook_name, guarded,
            ],
            check=True,
        )
@

Window cleanup removes the tracked window labels file when the pane
that created the tracked shell exits.  The guard still protects against
inherited cleanup hooks in descendant panes or windows.  Unlike the
session dispatcher hooks, this cleanup hook must be pane-scoped so it
disappears together with the pane that created the tracked shell.

<<helper functions>>=
def install_tmux_window_cleanup_hook(
    pane_id: str,
    window_id: str,
    who: str,
) -> None:
    """Install cleanup hook for tracked window labels file."""
    labels_file = window_labels_path(window_id, who)
    cleanup_cmd = (
        f"rm -f {shlex.quote(str(labels_file))}"
    )
    guarded = (
        "if-shell "
        f"'! tmux display-message -p -t {pane_id}"
        f' "" 2>/dev/null\' '
        f"{{ run-shell {shlex.quote(cleanup_cmd)} }}"
    )
    for hook_name in ("pane-exited", "pane-died"):
        subprocess.run(
            [
                "tmux", "set-hook", "-ap",
                "-t", pane_id,
                hook_name,
                guarded,
            ],
            check=True,
        )
@

The finalize command builder does not need a [[pane_id]] parameter
anymore---cleanup is handled by the hook above.

<<helper functions>>=
def build_detached_track_finalize_command(
    labels: List[str], who: str,
) -> str:
    """Return shell command to stop tracking when pane exits."""
    prefix = build_detached_nytid_prefix()
    label_args = " ".join(
        shlex.quote(lbl) for lbl in labels
    )
    cmd = (
        f"{prefix} "
        f"_stop-detached {label_args}"
    )
    if who != default_username:
        cmd += f" --who {shlex.quote(who)}"
    return cmd
@

The [[_stop-detached]] hidden command must also unregister labels from any
tracked tmux context.  Since [[_stop-detached]] runs inside the tmux pane,
[[$TMUX_PANE]] is available and the unregister logic can locate the correct
pane and window labels files.  Without this cleanup, labels from finished
detached commands accumulate in the pane labels file and interfere with
auto-suspend.

<<detached finalize command>>=
@cli.command(name="_stop-detached", hidden=True)
def stop_detached(
    labels: Annotated[List[str], detached_labels_arg],
    who: Annotated[str, who_opt] = default_username,
):
    """Stop labels quietly when a detached tmux pane exits."""
    session, completed_entries = stop_tracking_labels(
        who=who,
        labels=labels,
        quiet_if_missing=True,
    )
@

\subsubsection{Focus-Events Validation}

The [[pane-focus-out]]/[[pane-focus-in]] hooks require tmux's
[[focus-events]] option to be on.  Without it, the hooks never fire
and auto-suspend silently does nothing.  We warn the user at launch
time when the option is off.

<<helper functions>>=
def warn_if_focus_events_off() -> None:
    """Emit a warning if tmux focus-events is off."""
    try:
        result = subprocess.run(
            ["tmux", "show-option", "-gv",
             "focus-events"],
            capture_output=True,
            text=True,
            check=True,
        )
        if result.stdout.strip().lower() != "on":
            typer.echo(
                "Warning: tmux focus-events is off; "
                "auto-suspend hooks will not fire.  "
                "Run: tmux set -g focus-events on",
                err=True,
            )
    except (subprocess.CalledProcessError, OSError):
        pass
@

Let's verify the auto-suspend infrastructure with unit tests.
These test the pure-Python helpers without requiring tmux.

\paragraph{Config resolution.}
The [[should_auto_suspend]] resolver must follow the documented
priority: CLI flag beats per-worker config beats global config
beats the hard-coded default.

<<test functions>>=
def test_should_auto_suspend_cli_flag_wins(
    temp_tracking_dir,
):
    """CLI flag overrides all config."""
    assert should_auto_suspend("me", True) is True
    assert should_auto_suspend("me", False) is False

def test_should_auto_suspend_per_worker_config(
    temp_tracking_dir,
):
    """Per-worker config overrides global."""
    import typerconf as config
    config.set(
        f"{AUTO_SUSPEND_CONFIG}.default", "true"
    )
    config.set(
        f"{AUTO_SUSPEND_CONFIG}.alice", "false"
    )
    assert should_auto_suspend("alice", None) is False
    # Other worker falls through to global
    assert should_auto_suspend("bob", None) is True

def test_should_auto_suspend_global_config(
    temp_tracking_dir,
):
    """Global config overrides hard-coded default."""
    import typerconf as config
    config.set(
        f"{AUTO_SUSPEND_CONFIG}.default", "false"
    )
    assert should_auto_suspend("me", None) is False

def test_should_auto_suspend_hardcoded_default(
    temp_tracking_dir,
):
    """Hard-coded default is True when no config is set.

    Earlier tests may have set config keys that persist
    in the same process (typerconf has no delete method),
    so we mock [[config.get]] to always raise [[KeyError]]
    for auto-suspend keys.
    """
    import typerconf as _cfg
    _orig_get = _cfg.get
    def _no_auto_suspend(key, *args, **kwargs):
        if key.startswith(AUTO_SUSPEND_CONFIG):
            raise KeyError(key)
        return _orig_get(key, *args, **kwargs)
    with patch(
        "nytid.cli.track.config.get",
        side_effect=_no_auto_suspend,
    ):
        assert should_auto_suspend("me", None) is True
@

