\subsection{Listing Tracked Sessions}

The [[ls]] command fills a gap between [[status]] (which shows only the
\emph{currently active} session) and [[stats]] (which shows
\emph{aggregated} totals).  Sometimes you just want to see the last few
individual entries --- for example, to verify that yesterday's grading
session was recorded, or to eyeball recent work before writing a
timesheet.  The [[ls]] command provides this quick, per-entry view.

Unlike [[stats]], which defaults to a 1-day time window, [[ls]] uses a
count limit ([[-n]]) instead.  A time window would hide old entries even
when the user explicitly asks \enquote{show me my last 20 sessions}.
The count-based approach always returns exactly as many entries as
requested (or fewer if the history is shorter).

When the user wants to repair history, though, a bare timestamp line is
not enough: they need a stable way to name one specific entry.  The
optional [[--id]] flag (which is actually default now) prepends a short, unique 
prefix of each entry's [[content_hash()]], giving us Git-style identification 
without storing a separate persistent identifier.

<<argument and option definitions>>=
ls_labels_arg = typer.Argument(
    help="Filter by labels "
         "(shows all if not specified)",
    autocompletion=complete_historical_labels)
ls_number_opt = typer.Option(
    "--number", "-n",
    help="Number of entries to show")
ls_id_opt = typer.Option(
    "--id/--no-id",
    help="Remove column with content-hash "
         "prefixes for entries")
@

<<ls command>>=
@cli.command(name="ls")
def ls_entries(
    labels: Annotated[List[str],
                      ls_labels_arg] = None,
    n: Annotated[int, ls_number_opt] = 10,
    show_id: Annotated[bool, ls_id_opt] = True,
    who: Annotated[Optional[str],
                   who_filter_opt] = None,
):
    """
    List recent completed tracking entries.

    Use this to review the last few sessions, filter by course or worker, or
    show short IDs before editing or removing an entry.

    \b
    Examples:
      nytid track ls
      nytid track ls DD1310 -n 5
      nytid track ls --id
      nytid track ls --who Dan-Claude
    """
    <<load and filter for ls>>
    <<display ls entries>>
@

We use the shared [[filter_entries]] helper but skip the time-window
filter --- the count limit ([[-n]]) controls how many entries appear
instead:

<<load and filter for ls>>=
entries = filter_entries(who=who, labels=labels)
if not entries:
    typer.echo("No tracking data available.")
    return
@

Entries are sorted most-recent-first because the typical use case is
checking recent work --- older entries scroll off the terminal rather
than consuming attention.  Each entry shows start--end times so the
reader does not have to mentally add start plus duration.
Like [[stats]], the renderer uses a Rich table when writing
to a terminal and falls back to plain text for pipes:

<<display ls entries>>=
entries.sort(
    key=lambda e: e.start_time, reverse=True
)
hash_prefixes = abbreviate_hashes(
    [entry.content_hash() for entry in entries]
)
rows = []
for entry in entries[:n]:
    ts_start = entry.start_time.strftime(
        "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M"
    )
    ts_end = entry.end_time.strftime("%H:%M")
    dur = format_duration(entry.duration())
    lbl = get_labels_display(entry.labels)
    row = {
        "id": hash_prefixes[entry.content_hash()]
            if show_id else None,
        "time": f"{ts_start}\u2013{ts_end}",
        "dur": dur,
        "labels": lbl,
        "who": entry.who,
        "desc": entry.description or "",
    }
    rows.append(row)

if sys.stdout.isatty():
    <<render ls table with rich>>
else:
    <<render ls table as plain text>>
@

Rich gives us automatic column sizing so durations and labels
of varying width stay aligned --- the original plain-text
format produced ragged output that was hard to scan.  The
optional ID column is controlled by [[show_id]].

We import Rich lazily here (rather than at module level) because
this rendering path is not always reached, and the same pattern
is used by [[stats]]:

<<render ls table with rich>>=
from rich.console import Console
from rich import box
from rich.table import Table

console = Console()
table = Table(
    show_header=True, header_style="bold",
    box=box.SIMPLE, show_edge=False,
    pad_edge=False,
)
if show_id:
    table.add_column("ID", style="dim", no_wrap=True)
table.add_column("Time", style="cyan", no_wrap=True)
table.add_column(
    "Duration", justify="right", no_wrap=True
)
table.add_column("Labels", overflow="fold")
table.add_column("Who", no_wrap=True)
table.add_column("Description", overflow="fold")

for row in rows:
    cols = []
    if show_id:
        cols.append(row["id"])
    cols += [
        row["time"], row["dur"], row["labels"],
        row["who"], row["desc"],
    ]
    table.add_row(*cols)

console.print(table)
@

When stdout is not a terminal (e.g.\ piped through [[grep]]
or [[awk]]), Rich's box drawing and ANSI codes would corrupt
the output, so we fall back to one plain-text line per entry:

<<render ls table as plain text>>=
for row in rows:
    parts = []
    if show_id and row["id"]:
        parts.append(row["id"])
    parts += [
        row["time"], row["dur"], row["labels"],
        f"[{row['who']}]",
    ]
    if row["desc"]:
        parts.append(f"- {row['desc']}")
    typer.echo("  ".join(parts))
@

The same hash prefixes become the entry point for precise history
inspection and repair.  [[show]] prints one historical entry in full,
[[edit]] replaces one entry with updated content, and [[rm]] removes one
entry after confirmation.  All three resolve a hash prefix against the
current history so unrelated additions do not shift the user's target.

<<history entry helpers>>=
def parse_edit_tracking_start_time(
    at: Optional[str],
    original: TrackingEntry,
) -> datetime.datetime:
    """Return the edited start time for a historical entry."""
    if at is None:
        return original.start_time
    return parse_at_time(at, reference_time=original.start_time)

def parse_edit_tracking_end_time(
    end_at: Optional[str],
    duration_hours: Optional[float],
    start_time: datetime.datetime,
    original: TrackingEntry,
) -> datetime.datetime:
    """Return the edited end time for a historical entry."""
    if end_at is not None and duration_hours is not None:
        raise ValueError(
            "Cannot use both --end-at and --duration"
        )
    if end_at is not None:
        return parse_at_time(
            end_at,
            reference_time=original.end_time,
        )
    if duration_hours is not None:
        if duration_hours <= 0:
            raise ValueError("Duration must be positive")
        return start_time + datetime.timedelta(
            hours=duration_hours
        )
    return original.end_time

def render_tracking_entry(entry: TrackingEntry) -> List[str]:
    """Render one historical entry for human inspection."""
    return [
        f"ID: {entry.content_hash()}",
        f"Start: {entry.start_time.isoformat(sep=' ')}",
        f"End: {entry.end_time.isoformat(sep=' ')}",
        f"Duration: {format_duration(entry.duration())}",
        f"Labels: {get_labels_display(entry.labels)}",
        f"Who: {entry.who}",
        f"Description: {entry.description}" if entry.description else "Description:",
    ]
@

The [[show]], [[edit]], and [[rm]] commands all identify one entry by the
short hash prefix produced by [[track ls --id]].  We define the argument
once so the help text stays consistent across all three:

<<argument and option definitions>>=
entry_hash_arg = typer.Argument(
    ..., help="Tracking entry hash prefix")
@

<<show command>>=
@cli.command()
def show(
    entry_hash: Annotated[str, entry_hash_arg],
):
    """
    Show one historical tracking entry in full detail.

    Use this after `track ls --id` when you want to inspect timestamps,
    labels, worker, and description before editing or removing an entry.

    \b
    Example:
      nytid track show a1b2c3
    """
    entries = load_tracking_data()
    if not entries:
        typer.echo("No tracking data available.", err=True)
        raise typer.Exit(1)

    try:
        entry = resolve_tracking_entry(entries, entry_hash)
    except ValueError as exc:
        typer.echo(f"Error: {exc}", err=True)
        raise typer.Exit(1)

    for line in render_tracking_entry(entry):
        typer.echo(line)
@

Editing uses separate option constants from [[start]] because the
semantics differ: [[start --at]] sets a new session's start time, while
[[edit --at]] overwrites the start of an existing entry.  Reusing the
same constant would conflate these two meanings in the help text.

<<argument and option definitions>>=
edit_at_opt = typer.Option(
    "--at",
    help="Set start time "
         "(e.g. '14:30' or '2024-12-13 14:30')")
